Name: Li7P3S11
Text: The high ionic conductivity of the Li7P3S11 (SSE-220) reported in this work is comparable to the Li7P3S11 solid electrolyte obtained by mechanical milling (3.2 × 10−3 S cm−1 at RT, 30 h of synthesis process)11 or by liquid phase (1.5 × 10−3 S cm−1 at 25 °C, 37 h of synthesis process).14

Name: LLTO
Text: The bulk conductivity for the electrospun sample was on the order of 10−4 S cm−1, which is comparable to some LLTO samples that were synthesized using solid state method [30], [31].

Name: Na3PS4
Text: With a 3D pathway along the Na1 and Na2 sites in the open framework (Fig. 3(a)), cubic Na3PS4 (I43 m: a0 = 6.9965 Å) ceramic electrolyte owns a high conductivity at room temperature (∼10−4 S/cm) and a wide electrochemical window (5 V).

Name: Li4Ti5O12
Text: For the pristine Li4Ti5O12, an electrical conductivity of 2.9 × 10−9 S cm−1 was obtained, which is similar to the literature result [8], [34].

Name: Li4Ti4.9V0.1O12
Text: Electronic conductivity of argon calcined Li4Ti4.9V0.1O12 is 1.7 × 10−2 S cm−1 which is three orders higher than that of LTO.

Name: LATP-3 wt% Al2O3
Text: LATP-3 wt% Al2O3 exhibited a bulk conductivity of 4.24 × 10−4 S cm−1 and a grain boundary conductivity of 5.35 × 10−4 S cm−1.

Name: LiGe2(PO4)3
Text: Being a result of an interplay between the intrinsic conductivity, which depends on Li concentration, cell parameters etc., and the grain boundary conductivity determined by the microstructure, the reported values of specific conductivity range from 10−4 S cm−1 for LiTi2(PO4)3 to 1.3 × 10−3 S cm−1 for Li1+xAlxTi2−x(PO4)3 (ref. 16) or from 10−5 S cm−1 for LiGe2(PO4)3 to 2 × 10−4 S cm−1 for Li1.5Al0.5Ge1.5(PO4)3.

Name: PVDF–LiPAAOB GPE
Text: The ionic conductivity of the PVDF–LiPAAOB GPE at 25 °C is 0.35 mS cm−1, higher than that of Celgard 2730 saturated with the organic electrolyte (0.21 mS cm−1).

Name: Li3V2(PO4)3
Text: However, the intrinsic low electronic conductivity of Li3V2(PO4)3 (2.4 × 10−7 S cm−1 at room temperature) largely limits its rate performance.

Name: LiFePO4/C
Text: Significant decrease of impendence from bare LiFePO4 to LiFePO4/C is related to the improved conductivity. According to the formula σ = d/AR [30], the conductivities of LiFePO4/C and bare LiFePO4 are 4.4 × 10−6 and 2.1 × 10−6 S cm−1, respectively.

Name: Li6.4La2.3Na0.7Nb2O12
Text: Among the Li5 + 2xLa3-xNaxNb2O12 compounds investigated, the Na-substituted Li6.4La2.3Na0.7Nb2O12 exhibits the highest ionic conductivity of 1.6 × 10−4 S cm-1 at room temperature with an activation energy of 0.41 eV.

Name: Li7Ni0.2P3.1S11
Text: The 2 mol% Ni2P containing electrolyte (Li7Ni0.2P3.1S11) displays the highest lithium-ion conductivity of 2.22 mS cm−1 at room temperature, which is 1.6 times higher than pristine Li7P3S11

Name: Li3PO4
Text: The thin film is deposited by magnetron sputtering of Li3PO4 under N2-contained atmosphere, which introduces nitrogen into the Li3PO4 and raises the conductivity from 7 × 10−8 to 2 × 10−6 S cm−1.

Name: 1M LiPF6 in PC
Text: In agreement with the viscosity values, 1 M LiPF6 in EC:DEC (3:7 wt%) displays the highest conductivity (6.0 mS cm−1) followed by 1 M LiPF6 in PC (5.4 mS cm−1) and 1 M LiPF6 in PC:MTFMP (9:1 wt%) (5.1 mS cm−1).

Name: PEO-NH4F
Text: However the value of conductivity for PEO–NH4F polymer electrolytes is low (10−6 S/cm) and hence not suitable for use in various solid state ionic devices.

Name: CPE-4
Text: The conductivity of the highest conducting sample, CPE-4, is calculated to be 2.44 × 10−6 S cm−1 at room temperature.

Name: CuBO2
Text: Recently [Cu2S2][Sr3Sc2O5] was found to have possess a band gap of 3.1 eV, coupled with an undoped p-type conductivity measured at 2.8 S cm−1, which is higher than the best undoped delafossite system (CuBO2, 1.65 S cm−1),57,98 and is two orders of magnitude higher than undoped LaCuOS (0.01–0.1 S cm−1.99

Name: 1g2-MA-TFSI/LiTFSI
Text: As can be observed in Fig. 5, for the PILs electrolytes system 1g2-MA-PF6/LiPF6, 1g2-MA-ClO4/LiClO4 and 1g2-MA-TFSI/LiTFSI, the ionic conductivity values of the samples increases with the corresponding lithium salt content up to 45 wt%, 45 wt% and 30 wt%, respectively, and the corresponding maximum values of the ionic conductivity are 7.41 × 10−5 S cm−1, 7.76 × 10−5 S cm−1 and 3.02 × 10−6 S cm−1, after which the values of the conductivity start decrease.

Name: Pure CA
Text: Table 1 illustrates that the ionic conductivity increases with increase in NH4NO3 and attains a maximum value of 1.024 × 10−3 at room temperature for 50CA:50NH4NO3, which has greater ionic conductivity than that of pure CA (1.285 × 10−7 S cm−1).

Name: polyindole
Text: In its doped state, polyindole is green, with an electrical conductivity in the range of 5 × 10−4–8 × 10−2 S cm−1, slightly depending on the nature of the counter-ion [5].
